<br>
It is quite obvious that U.N. resolutions against Israel outnumber those against Palestine (or the P.L.O. or Palestinians in general) for the main reason that most U.N. resolutions are against nations and governments.  The Palestinians have no nation to speak of at this time, their &quot;government&quot; is technically in exile and the P.L.O only has observer status at the U.N.  Resolutions against such a nebulous entity can be difficult to enforce.<br>
<br>
Notwithstanding that previous fact, the Palestinians have resisted Resolutions 242 and 338 as well as the Oslo accord.  I tried to find other resolutions they resisted, but I could not find any others.<br>
<br>
Israel has resisted approximately 65 resolutions from 1955 to 1992.  Another 20 resolutions from 1993 to 1995 passed by the General Assembly have been resisted, but as these are only General Assembly resolutions, they are not binding anyway.<br>
<br>
Additionally, the U.S. has VETOed approximately 34 Security Council resolutions against Israel from 1972 to the present.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Let he who is without sin cast the first stone.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Agreed.  Neither side is without sin.  I won't get into a which is worse debate comparing suicide bombings of buses filled with innocents to things like an air raid bombing of an apartment building to kill a Hamas leader that also killed innocents.  Both are reprehensible.<br>
<br>
I pray this latest initiative brings some peace to the area.  Too many innocent people die there, on both sides. <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
