Re. your post no. 24 you state:  <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You may want to ask yourself if the Canon was closed, how is it the great Codex Sinaiticus;4th century; has books of Epistle of Barnabas and most of the Shepherd of Hermas.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> I have done so, Jeff, and concluded those books were initially included because Constantine wanted them included.  It was he who 'commissioned' the preparation of the codex.  To the best of my knowledge they were not part of the work done by Eusibius on Constantine's behalf.<br>
