<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.angelfire.com/folk/jeffthefinn/lerins2.html" target="top">THE COMMONITORY OF ST. VINCENT OF LERINS</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->: Chapter 2<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But here some one perhaps will ask, Since the canon of Scripture is complete, and sufficient of itself for everything, and more than sufficient, what need is there to join with it the authority of the Church's interpretation? For this reason, - because, owing to the depth of Holy Scripture, all do not accept it in one and the same sense, but one understands its words in one way, another in another; so that it seems to be capable of as many interpretations as there are interpreters. For Novatian expounds it one way, Sabellius another, Donatus another, Arius, Eunomius, Macedonius, another, Photinus, Apollinaris, Priscillian, another, Iovinian, Pelagius, Celestius, another, lastly, Nestorius another. Therefore, it is very necessary, on account of so great intricacies of such various error, that the rule for the right understanding of the prophets and apostles should be framed in accordance with the standard of Ecclesiastical and Catholic interpretation. <br>
Moreover, in the Catholic Church itself, all possible care must be taken, that we hold that faith which has been believed everywhere, always, by all. For that is truly and in the strictest sense &quot;Catholic,&quot; which, as the name itself and the reason of the thing declare, comprehends all universally. This rule we shall observe if we follow universality, antiquity, consent. We shall follow universality if we confess that one faith to be true, which the whole Church throughout the world confesses; antiquity, if we in no wise depart from those interpretations which it is manifest were notoriously held by our holy ancestors and fathers; consent, in like manner, if in antiquity itself we adhere to the consentient<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
Mr Baker:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The Roman Church leaders wanted it one way, the Greek Church leaders wanted it another way, and the true canon was lost in the shuffle because those who were following usin the New Testament as originally written in the order in which they were arranged, were loving their neighbors as themselves rather than trying to make a name for themselves.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I have quite enough occupy my mind with in what is written in the Bible.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I asked you to name names and sources of who was trying to make names for themselves?  So, you have been reading other books besides the Bible, and I would bet that it was a dispensationalist and he got his stuff from Darby and Cyrus Scofield.<br>
Jeff the Finn<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus" target="top">Nilus</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=charlesbaker>Charles Baker</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered Member</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#B87333>(6/9/03 12:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A Question to Jeff and Esdras.</span><hr size=1> Dear Jeff:<br>
<br>
You have asked for scriptures that have led me to my conclusions.<br>
<br>
First there are the promises of land to Abraham, Isaac and Jacob, as well as the promises of a future, for Israel, contained in Isaiah, Jermiah, and Ezekiel, that have still to be fulfilled.<br>
<br>
There are the prophecies in Daniel about the Israelites, that have never been fulfilled.<br>
<br>
Daniel has a number of rather detailed prophecies, Jeff, stating with the 70 weeks (of years) and ending with Daniel 12:11 and 12.  Some have been fulfilled and some not.  It is the ones that have not been fulfilled that interest me.<br>
<br>
Then there are the prophecies of Zepheniah and Zechariah, along with the fill-in prophecies of the minor prophets.<br>
<br>
These all tell of an endtimes, latter day, future for Israel in the Holy Land.  Prophecies that have not yet been fulfilled. <br>
<br>
We then have the prophecies given to us by Our Lord relating to believers, both Jew and Gentile, most of which are still to be fulfilled including I Thess.4:16:17 and I Cor.15:51-52.<br>
<br>
These last are remarkable prophecies, Jeff.  Prophecies that believers should be wondering about and pondering on because they have not been fulfilled, yet, but they will be!  I believe God's word, you see. <br>
<br>
Finally there are the prophecies of the Revelation of Jesus Christ starting with the messages to the 7 churches.  Once I was introduced to what the Bible holds in store, by some men who have explored its vast reaches themselves, I began exploring it for my self.  <br>
<br>
If you cannot accept my sincerity, I can do nothing about it.  I am sorry you do not see things as I do but you must study the Bible for yourself.  No one else can do it for you.  <br>
<br>
Don't take any man's word for anything, Jeff, regarding the Bible that is. Check it out for yourself!  The Bible, that is, not books that are not a recognized canonized part of it.<br>
<br>
Rev. 22:18-19 merit very careful consideration, in this respect, Jeff:  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>For I testify unto every man that heareth the words of the prophecy of this book, If any man shall add unto these things, God shall add unto him the plagues that are written in this book: and if any man shall take away from the words of the book of this prophecy, God shall take away his part out of the book of life, and out of the holy city, and from the things which are written in this book.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Many limit the application of that warning to the last book of the Bible but I am convinced it applies to the whole book, the Bible itself.<br>
<br>
God's word it truth!  Those who worhsip Him, must worship Him in spirit and in truth.  John 4:23-24<br>
<br>
God Bless you.  Charlie Baker. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jeffthefinn>jeffthefinn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/finnbutton.GIF" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered Member</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#B87333>(6/9/03 1:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/jfinn.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: A Question to Jeff and Esdras.</span><hr size=1> How did you get your New Testament, who picked the books and when?  It did not fall out of the sky in bonded leather.  <br>
As I pointed out Daniel was written in 165 BC and it was an Apoclypse and the 70 weeks were talking about things that were taking place when he wrote it.  <br>
I have read and there is nothing at all to support dispensationalism, and that is where it stands, it comes from Darby, Scofield, Lindsey, and now in the latest fiction of Jenkins.  <br>
